  "school": "ICT",
  "definition": "A directional expectation for the next trading day derived from the prior daily candle's closure relative to previous day's high/low and its wick size, anticipating either a reversal (sweep and close back inside range) or continuation (close outside range). Lower-time-frame change in state of delivery confirms the bias, which filters all lower-time-frame entry setups.",
  "identification_rules": [
    "Mark previous day high, low, and equilibrium as reference levels, along with swing highs/lows and relative equal highs/lows to identify stop clusters.",
    "Check if prior liquidity has been swept to determine distribution direction (upside or downside).",
    "To establish daily bias, examine the prior daily candle's close relative to previous day high (PDH) and previous day low (PDL). A close above PDH indicates bullish continuation; a close below PDL indicates bearish continuation.",
    "A sweep of PDH or PDL followed by a close back inside the prior day's range signals a reversal bias: a sweep of PDH and close below it is bearish reversal; a sweep of PDL and close above is bullish reversal.",
    "If the daily candle forms a shallow wick, anticipate same-day expansion in the bias direction; a large opposing wick signals limited expansion and requires waiting for the next daily candle (candle 3) before trading continuation.",
    "Confirm the daily bias by checking for a change in state of delivery (CISD) on a lower time frame: on the hourly or 30-minute chart during Asia/London session, or on the 5- or 15-minute chart during New York session, price must close through the opposing candles that formed the swept high/low.",
    "In a bullish continuation scenario, hourly closures below the previous day's equilibrium (EQ) reduce the probability of upside expansion; such closures should be avoided.",
    "Identify a daily point of interest (POI) such as a swing high, swing low, or fair value gap; a candle 2 closure (current candle sweeps prior high/low and closes back inside) or reversal candle forming inside the POI confirms the reversal bias and targets the next day's expansion.",
    "If the daily candle fails to displace beyond PDH or PDL (i.e., price approaches but does not close outside), shift bias: failure to close above PDH turns bias bearish targeting PDL; failure to close below PDL turns bias bullish targeting PDH.",
    "Consider higher time frame context: a weekly reversal candle or weekly continuation pattern influences daily bias direction; an overall uptrend (higher highs/lows) supports bullish bias, downtrend supports bearish.",
    "The previous day high and low serve as liquidity targets (draw on liquidity) for the bias-driven expansion.",
    "Do not assign bias on consolidation days when the daily candle fails to take either side of the range.",
    "Bias is fractal: when using a lower entry time frame (e.g., 5-minute), the hourly candle closure can substitute for the daily closure as the bias-defining time frame.",
    "On the daily chart, mark key levels: previous day high/low, daily order blocks, daily fair value gaps (FVG), swing highs/lows.",
    "Look for daily candle closes inside FVG or reversal candles closing back inside the previous candle's range as bias confirmation signals.",
    "Identify sell-side liquidity (above swing highs) or buy-side liquidity (below swing lows) as liquidity targets.",
    "In a trend, previous day highs/lows from up to 3 days back can serve as reference levels."
  ],
  "trading_implication": "Daily bias acts as a top-down filter: only setups aligned with the bias direction are taken. It defines the draw on liquidity (previous day high or low) and the expected expansion or retracement. When the wick supports expansion, target full swing extremes; when the wick is large, wait for the next candle (candle 3) and target conservative levels. Confirm with lower-time-frame change in state of delivery. Skip days with no clear bias or already taken liquidity. Align daily, 4-hour, and 15-minute expansion for optimal entries with minimum 2R targets.",
  "common_mistakes": [
    "Expecting a large expansion move or trading same-day expansion when the daily candle has a large opposing wick, instead of waiting for the next daily candle (candle 3) or adjusting targets.",
    "Accepting hourly closures below the previous day's equilibrium (EQ) on a bullish continuation expectation, which reduces setup probability.",
    "Entering or accepting daily bias without a lower-time-frame change in state of delivery (CISD) confirmation, or using the wrong time frame for confirmation (e.g., hourly during New York instead of 5/15-minute).",
    "Switching bias intraday after a single counter-move instead of waiting for the daily candle closure.",
    "Taking lower-time-frame reversal signals that contradict the daily bias or are not confirmed by a daily closure.",
    "Forcing entries on choppy or consolidation days when there is no clear bias, no protected swing aligned, or no side of the range being taken.",
    "Misidentifying daily phases (e.g., labeling consolidation as retracement) leading to incorrect bias assignment.",
    "Switching between different bias frameworks instead of committing to a single consistent method.",
    "Entering on a lower time frame without first establishing the daily bias (skipping the top-down step).",
    "Attempting to trade the wick of the higher time frame candle instead of waiting for the wick to form and trading the body/continuation.",
    "Attempting a shallow reversal entry after price has already moved a large range, without waiting for CISD and expansion-met-with-expansion.",
    "Assuming a close back inside the range immediately reverses the bias when the higher time frame trend remains intact.",
    "Entering when the draw on liquidity (previous day high/low) has already been swept earlier in the session, leaving no remaining target.",
    "Treating a sweep that does not close back inside the range (no candle 2 closure or reversal candle) as a valid bias signal.",
    "Entering immediately at the daily sweep level without waiting for a lower-time-frame protected swing, continuation entry, or candle 3 setup.",
    "Trading candle 3 expansion when the target draw on liquidity has already been reached.",
    "Mistaking a continuation candle that closes into a recent low or high as a reversal candle for bias purposes.",
    "Taking entries on a 4-hour or hourly candle that has already traded against the bias direction first, rather than waiting for a new candle to open on side.",
    "Only judging bias based on single daily candle direction or single candle pattern, ignoring the importance of displacement.",
    "Changing bias when a bullish candle appears in a still bearish structure; wait for structure confirmation (e.g., order block validation) before adjusting.",
    "Not considering other daily structure factors like FVG that affect bias.",
    "Assuming a trading opportunity exists every day; bias determination still requires specific entry points on lower time frames.",
    "Rushing to determine bias before the daily candle fully closes, leading to overturned bias.",
    "Ignoring the specific locations of daily key levels (FVG, swing points) and judging direction by feel.",
    "Trading without waiting for lower-time-frame confirmation after establishing bias, violating multi-timeframe alignment.",
    "Misinterpreting a close inside previous day's range as a valid bias; wait for clear breakout confirmation.",
    "Trading on hourly or 5-minute charts without establishing daily bias first, leading to trades against daily trend.",
    "Judging bias based solely on a single daily candle pattern, ignoring larger timeframe market structure.",
    "Persisting with bearish bias when price fails to displace below a swing high, leading to stop-outs."
  ],
